Biography: Amiangshu Bosu received the PhD degree in computer science from the University of Alabama in 2015 with a thesis identifying the characteristics and benefits of contemporary code review practices. His research interests lie in the areas of empirical software engineering, peer code review, software security, android security, malware detection, cybersecurity, mining software repositories, empirical software engineering, and social network analysis. He is a member of the IEEE and ACM.(Based on document published on 7 June 2016).

Biography: Karen is a senior analyst at the National Center for Science and Engineering Statistics at NSF. Name: Filkov
Affiliation: Doctor of PhilosophyProfessor at University of California, Davis United States (But on GoogleScholar he is a Professor of Computer Science, UC Davis)???
Biography: I am a data scientist working on big data sets. In our DECAL research group we develop theory and methods (based on statistical models and data mining) to aid in the understanding of and improving the software engineering processes in complex, distributed and collaborative socio-technical environments (mostly OSS projects). We are finding that the social component is necessary for understanding the technical contributions and vice-versa. With plant biologists from the US Forest Service and UCD we study interesting properties of plants and tie them to the underlying biochemistry of their gene networks. In particular, we conduct RNA-seq, ChIP-seq, and other experiments, and then integrate the large-scale genomic data sets coming out of them into biological models of plant growth.

Name: Fotrousi
Affiliation: Postdoctoral Researcher at University of Hamburg
Biography: Farnaz is a Software Engineer and researcher. She is interested in applied research, combining her over twelve years of industrial experience in software companies with research knowledge. Her main research interests are in continuous software evolution, software product management, user feedback for modeling the product success, requirement engineering, and software ethics. Her current research is on Feedback Bots and their applications in Requirements Engineering and Continuous Evolution of Software Systems. She is the program chair of SEthics 2021 (International Workshop on Ethics in Software Engineering Research and practice) and the proceeding chair of RE2021. She has successfully organized two other workshops, REthics 2021 and IWSPM 2016, and served in the PC of conferences and workshops, including RE, REFSQ, RCIS, ClowdRE, and IWSPM. She collaborated on four European projects, namely FI-STAR, SUPERSEDE, Wise-IOT, and IoD.

Biography: H. Siegfried Stiehl was born in 1951 and received the Ing.Grad. degree in electrical engineering from the Fachhochschule Furtwangen, Germany, in 1973. He received the Diploma degree in computer science, the degree Dipl.-Inf., in 1976, and the Dr.-Ing. degree in 1980, both from the Department of Computer Science, Technical University of Berlin, Berlin, Germany.,He was an Assistant Professor from 1982 to 1988 and achieved the venia legendi for computer vision through his habilitation in 1987 at the Technical University Berlin, Berlin, Germany. In 1988 he was appointed as Associate Professor in the Faculty of Informatics at the University of Hamburg, Hamburg, Germany, and since, has been with the cognitive systems research group. Since 2001 he has served as Dean of the Faculty of Informatics. He is a member of the editorial boards of Journal of Mathematical Imaging and Vision, Biological Cybernetics, and Image and Vision Computing. His research interests include information processing models of visual perception, computational neuroscience, computer vision, and biomedical image computing.(Based on document published on 22 July 2003).
